The fluorescence intensities of N–MoS2 QDs solution were recorded following the addition of different concentrations of curcumin. With the increase of curcumin concentration from 0 to 20 μM, the FL emission intensity of N–MoS2 QDs decreased gradually (Fig. 4
                        A). A well-defined linear relationship was achieved between the FL intensity of MoS2 QDs and the curcumin concentrations ranging from 0.1 to 10 μM with a detection limit of 59 nM (Fig. 4B). The relative standard deviations of peak fluorescence readings were 2.8 %, 3.1 %, and 2.6 % in three repetitive assays of 0.5 μM, 1 μM, and 2.5 μM curcumin, respectively, indicating that our proposed method has a good reproducibility. Compared to as-published methods for curcumin determination, this proposed method can provide preferable detection performance in aspects of LOD (Table 1
                        ).

The practical application of the as-proposed IFE-based sensor in the detection of curcumin was achieved by using the standard addition method in water and human urine samples. Good recovery rates were achieved in the range of 99.65 %–104.9 % with RSDs of less than 4.6 %, indicating that the method has good accuracy and precision (Table 2
                        ). All results were consistent with those from HPLC (Table 2). As shown in Table 3
                        , the curcumin contents in original extractions of ginger powder samples, mustard samples, and curry powder samples detected by the proposed sensor were 4.32 μM, 2.09 μM, and 3.08 μM, respectively. Meanwhile, different concentrations of curcumin were spiked into ginger powder samples, mustard samples, and curry samples extractions, and good recovery rates were achieved in range of 96.0 %–104.5 % with RSDs of less than 3.6 %, all results were consistent with those from HPLC (Table 3). Herein, the as-proposed sensor shows great potential for the curcumin detection in the safety and quality testing of actual samples.

To study the potential application of N–MoS2 QDs in the biomedical field, an MTT assay was conducted in HeLa cells. The MTT results indicated that N–MoS2 QDs had no significant cytotoxicity at the concentration of 0–500 μg/mL of N–MoS2 QDs, indicating their good biocompatibility (Fig. 6
                        ). Then, the N–MoS2 QDs were incubated with HeLa cells to demonstrate their cellular imaging capabilities. As shown in Fig. 7
                        , after incubation with N–MoS2 QDs the HeLa cells showed a strong blue color. The FL intensity of N–MoS2 QDs (400 μg/mL−1) was increased with incubation time until it reached a steady-state after 6 h. Therefore, 6 h was selected as the optimal imaging conditions. The result indicated that the N–MoS2 QDs exhibited relatively low cytotoxicity and could be applied for fluorescence-based imaging of biological samples.
